WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.166
So in the last lecture I spent
quite a while trying to convey a

00:00:05.166 --> 00:00:08.754
sense of
how the structure of DNA was

00:00:08.754 --> 00:00:09.836
discovered.

00:00:09.836 --> 00:00:13.690
The crystallographic
data that led to it,

00:00:13.690 --> 00:00:17.492
as I said, was collected by
Rosalind Franklin.

00:00:17.492 --> 00:00:20.465
And
I saw there was some confusion

00:00:20.465 --> 00:00:24.000
about this picture that I showed
you next.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.000
This is not a photograph of a
double helix.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.465
This is what happened when she
bounced the x-ray off the

00:00:33.465 --> 00:00:34.551
crystal of
DNA.

00:00:34.551 --> 00:00:37.498
This is the diffraction pattern
that she saw.

00:00:37.498 --> 00:00:40.037
And then one
works backwards from that

00:00:40.037 --> 00:00:42.856
trying to figure out what kind
of structure it

00:00:42.856 --> 00:00:46.167
was that would have caused that
diffraction pattern.

00:00:46.167 --> 00:00:48.842
And you have
to be a pretty good x-ray

00:00:48.842 --> 00:00:51.428
crystallographer to draw any
kind of

00:00:51.428 --> 00:00:52.856
inferences from that.

00:00:52.856 --> 00:00:55.714
And there were people,
including Francis

00:00:55.714 --> 00:01:00.000
Crick, who saw the implications
of it right away.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.462
But the point was she collected
the data and then two people

00:01:03.462 --> 00:01:06.138
that I told
you about then whose name you

00:01:06.138 --> 00:01:08.569
know so well,
Jim Watson and Francis

00:01:08.569 --> 00:01:12.855
Crick, were the two individuals
that came up with the model that

00:01:12.855 --> 00:01:15.064
explained the diffraction
pattern.

00:01:15.064 --> 00:01:18.692
And therefore we learned the
structure of DNA as a

00:01:18.692 --> 00:01:20.318
double-stranded helix.

00:01:20.318 --> 00:01:23.298
I also tried
to make the case that it wasn't

00:01:23.298 --> 00:01:25.712
two geniuses who sat down in the
room,

00:01:25.712 --> 00:01:30.000
took a look at this and popped
up with the model.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.334
It was a story of real people
with misadventures and mistakes

00:01:34.334 --> 00:01:36.928
and
recovery from mistakes and so

00:01:36.928 --> 00:01:37.971
on getting it.

00:01:37.971 --> 00:01:40.390
It was also a very
small group.

00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:44.305
And I'm going to take just a
very small minute at the

00:01:44.305 --> 00:01:47.900
beginning of the class because
I have a colleague,

00:01:47.900 --> 00:01:51.179
Vernon Ingram
who's sitting down here in the

00:01:51.179 --> 00:01:53.845
front, who was a member of this
very

00:01:53.845 --> 00:01:57.252
small group with Jim Watson and
Francis Crick.

00:01:57.252 --> 00:02:00.425
So he was there
where all this happened.

00:02:00.425 --> 00:02:03.141
And almost nobody in the world
has

00:02:03.141 --> 00:02:06.824
had a chance in your generation
to hear directly from somebody

00:02:06.824 --> 00:02:08.921
who was
there when it happened.

00:02:08.921 --> 00:02:11.713
So asked Vernon if he would
come and just

00:02:11.713 --> 00:02:15.455
talk to you for a little bit
just what it was like to be

00:02:15.455 --> 00:02:16.000
there.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:40.848
Well, thanks,
Graham.

00:02:40.848 --> 00:03:01.864
You seem to
be at a very exciting state in

00:03:01.864 --> 00:03:03.000
7.014.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.991
This structure of the secret of
life no less.

00:03:07.991 --> 00:03:13.937
And it is interesting
that immediately when Watson

00:03:13.937 --> 00:03:18.427
and Crick put together a model
of the

00:03:18.427 --> 00:03:24.688
DNA molecule that fit the x-ray
data, that was the point,

00:03:24.688 --> 00:03:28.947
how do you
know a model is correct?

00:03:28.947 --> 00:03:33.271
Because there are certain
distances

00:03:33.271 --> 00:03:37.065
in the model,
and those have to correlate

00:03:37.065 --> 00:03:42.543
exactly with the distances
of the x-ray spots in the

00:03:42.543 --> 00:03:46.361
diffraction pattern that you
saw.

00:03:46.361 --> 00:03:51.868
That is how you know that a
model that you've built to

00:03:51.868 --> 00:03:55.828
certain
specifications corresponds to

00:03:55.828 --> 00:03:59.454
what the molecule of itself in
the

00:03:59.454 --> 00:04:06.000
crystal that you're examining
actually is composed of.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:12.500
It was by sheer accident that I
happened to be working as a

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:17.741
biochemist in the MRC,
The Medical Research Council

00:04:17.741 --> 00:04:21.640
lab at the
Cavendish Laboratory where

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:24.687
Watson and Crick were working.

00:04:24.687 --> 00:04:26.625
Sheer
accident.

00:04:26.625 --> 00:04:32.000
It was a very crowded lab,
as Graham said.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.821
And that's something that you
should remember.

00:04:36.821 --> 00:04:41.154
When you're choosing a
lab to work in,

00:04:41.154 --> 00:04:45.235
always go to a lab that's
overcrowded.

00:04:45.235 --> 00:04:50.632
Never go to a
lab where there's lots of space

00:04:50.632 --> 00:04:57.392
because a really successful lab
attracts so many coworkers,

00:04:57.392 --> 00:05:02.000
visitors that it rapidly gets
overcrowded.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.603
And that was the case in this
laboratory.

00:05:06.603 --> 00:05:10.042
The director was Max
Perutz.

00:05:10.042 --> 00:05:16.500
Co-director John Kendrew doing
x-ray crystallography of

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:22.422
proteins for almost the first
time, and solving the protein

00:05:22.422 --> 00:05:23.750
structure.

00:05:23.750 --> 00:05:29.489
Francis Crick was a graduate
student of Max Perutz's doing

00:05:29.489 --> 00:05:31.000
his PhD work.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.538
And the first thing I remember
about Francis was when I went

00:05:35.538 --> 00:05:38.674
there as a
biochemist to work with Max

00:05:38.674 --> 00:05:42.076
Perutz, when I went there,
there was this

00:05:42.076 --> 00:05:46.690
tall gangling guy constantly
circulating between the top

00:05:46.690 --> 00:05:48.657
floor of
the building,

00:05:48.657 --> 00:05:53.151
his office in the middle and
the x-ray machines at the

00:05:53.151 --> 00:05:53.730
bottom.

00:05:53.730 --> 00:05:56.623
He was constantly going up and
down.

00:05:56.623 --> 00:06:00.943
And in those days the
buildings didn't have an

00:06:00.943 --> 00:06:04.228
elevators or lifts as the
English

00:06:04.228 --> 00:06:05.856
called them.

00:06:05.856 --> 00:06:10.912
So he was in excellent physical
shape.

00:06:10.912 --> 00:06:13.907
Very crowded,
a very modest lab.

00:06:13.907 --> 00:06:19.983
And what's usually forgotten
is a key member of that group,

00:06:19.983 --> 00:06:23.665
an engineer,
Tony Broad, key person

00:06:23.665 --> 00:06:29.189
because he invented what was
then the world's best and most

00:06:29.189 --> 00:06:32.361
efficient
x-ray machine,

00:06:32.361 --> 00:06:37.000
a rotating anode x-ray machine.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:43.311
And because to the x-ray
crystallographers in that group

00:06:43.311 --> 00:06:46.231
this
machine was available,

00:06:46.231 --> 00:06:51.000
because of that they were the
preeminent x-ray

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.123
structure group in the world.

00:06:54.123 --> 00:06:58.000
My job was as a biochemist,
protein

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.283
biochemist, putting a heavy
atom, mercury,

00:07:02.283 --> 00:07:09.520
very heavy atom into Max
Parutz's hemoglobin crystals in

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:12.000
specific places.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.369
That has a predictable effect
on the x-ray pattern and that

00:07:17.369 --> 00:07:20.637
enables the
Fourier diagram to be

00:07:20.637 --> 00:07:25.331
constructed with real phase
values for the x-ray

00:07:25.331 --> 00:07:31.027
diffractions,
for the physicists among you

00:07:31.027 --> 00:07:32.000
here.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.692
Are there any physicists here?

00:07:35.692 --> 00:07:38.030
Yeah, I thought so.

00:07:38.030 --> 00:07:43.380
That was a big
step forward and that was also

00:07:43.380 --> 00:07:48.000
a big step in figuring out the
structure

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:54.814
of the DNA samples
semi-crystals that Professor

00:07:54.814 --> 00:07:58.271
Walker
just referred to.

00:07:58.271 --> 00:08:03.083
All dependent on the engineer
Tony

00:08:03.083 --> 00:08:07.707
Broad who is never mentioned in
any of these histories,

00:08:07.707 --> 00:08:11.803
but without him
this would not have happened.

00:08:11.803 --> 00:08:15.415
So it was an exciting place to
work in,

00:08:15.415 --> 00:08:16.613
very exciting.

00:08:16.613 --> 00:08:19.268
We were all young in those
days.

00:08:19.268 --> 00:08:24.262
And living the lives of
young men and young women with

00:08:24.262 --> 00:08:27.747
all the complications that arise
when

00:08:27.747 --> 00:08:32.326
you put a whole bunch of very
energetic young men,

00:08:32.326 --> 00:08:36.118
very energetic
young women together.

00:08:36.118 --> 00:08:40.000
And by that I mean the
interpersonal

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:43.718
relationships which when you're
in a crowded,

00:08:43.718 --> 00:08:47.846
very active situation can
sometimes interfere.

00:08:47.846 --> 00:08:52.000
And always very entertaining,
I can tell you

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:52.434
that.

00:08:52.434 --> 00:08:55.391
I could give you chapter and
verse.

00:08:55.391 --> 00:09:02.285
But it isn't really so very
different from people your age

00:09:02.285 --> 00:09:04.000
now, right?

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.456
I mean I'm not saying it
interferes with you,

00:09:08.456 --> 00:09:10.380
sometimes it might.

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:13.323
But
it was an exciting lab,

00:09:13.323 --> 00:09:18.179
an exciting time to be there
because we were not

00:09:18.179 --> 00:09:24.288
the only group trying to figure
out the structure of DNA.

00:09:24.288 --> 00:09:28.652
A huge
competitor was Linus Pauling at

00:09:28.652 --> 00:09:34.212
Caltech who had beaten that same
group once before,

00:09:34.212 --> 00:09:37.912
quite recently,
over the alpha helix,

00:09:37.912 --> 00:09:42.636
the crucial
component of protein structure.

00:09:42.636 --> 00:09:46.332
He got the right answer first,
1.5

00:09:46.332 --> 00:09:50.082
angstrom reflection,
the alpha helix.

00:09:50.082 --> 00:09:52.999
And our group,
Max Parutz

00:09:52.999 --> 00:09:55.884
and our group had been wrong.

00:09:55.884 --> 00:09:59.664
So the group was smarting under
that

00:09:59.664 --> 00:10:02.733
kind of defeat,
if you like.

00:10:02.733 --> 00:10:07.166
And competition is a wonderful
spur,

00:10:07.166 --> 00:10:12.284
as long as you don't let it get
out of hand.

00:10:12.284 --> 00:10:18.581
Well, needless to say we
didn't, but the competition

00:10:18.581 --> 00:10:23.832
with the Pauling lab was
certainly so severe

00:10:23.832 --> 00:10:27.598
that we awaited the next
letter.

00:10:27.598 --> 00:10:33.608
You see, in those days new
scientific information arrived

00:10:33.608 --> 00:10:37.000
not by publications,
that too much too

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.558
long, but by personal letter.

00:10:39.558 --> 00:10:43.000
And, in fact,
the NIH has put together

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:48.104
all these various letters in
the Francis Crick collection.

00:10:48.104 --> 00:10:51.676
And when
you have time you should look

00:10:51.676 --> 00:10:52.507
at those.

00:10:52.507 --> 00:10:57.647
They're quite interesting
because they tell you in a way

00:10:57.647 --> 00:11:01.000
a scientific paper does not tell
you.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.426
What I feel about my experiment
results.

00:11:04.426 --> 00:11:08.494
What she feels about her
experiment results.

00:11:08.494 --> 00:11:12.599
What it means to me as a
person, to her as a

00:11:12.599 --> 00:11:14.901
person, to him as a person.

00:11:14.901 --> 00:11:18.399
So we were constantly watching
the mail

00:11:18.399 --> 00:11:23.358
and discussing the news as it
came in, mostly over a beer at

00:11:23.358 --> 00:11:25.517
the pub
next door.

00:11:25.517 --> 00:11:30.000
It was very conveniently
located.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:35.770
But being a small group crowded
together made communication

00:11:35.770 --> 00:11:39.274
within
our group very easy indeed.

00:11:39.274 --> 00:11:41.013
And we had fights.

00:11:41.013 --> 00:11:44.018
I don't mean physical
fights.

00:11:44.018 --> 00:11:46.468
We had scientific fights.

00:11:46.468 --> 00:11:49.998
And as a biochemist I was able
to

00:11:49.998 --> 00:11:55.782
settle a crucial fight among
the crystallographers Crick and

00:11:55.782 --> 00:11:59.350
Watson
who were building the model.

00:11:59.350 --> 00:12:02.899
Because, quite frankly,
they didn't

00:12:02.899 --> 00:12:04.740
know much chemistry.

00:12:04.740 --> 00:12:08.698
And were trying to build a
model with the

00:12:08.698 --> 00:12:11.893
wrong confirmation of the
peptide bond.

00:12:11.893 --> 00:12:17.086
They didn't realize that the
peptide bond has two possible

00:12:17.086 --> 00:12:18.335
confirmations.

00:12:18.335 --> 00:12:22.904
And they had at one
point a terrible time trying to

00:12:22.904 --> 00:12:26.099
fit everything together because
they

00:12:26.099 --> 00:12:28.877
were using the wrong
confirmation.

00:12:28.877 --> 00:12:32.076
I'm talking about lactam-lactim
for

00:12:32.076 --> 00:12:37.845
those of you who are organic
chemists and it means something,

00:12:37.845 --> 00:12:39.372
a
confirmation.

00:12:39.372 --> 00:12:44.384
And once they got the first
confirmation then the model

00:12:44.384 --> 00:12:46.210
clicked into place.

00:12:46.210 --> 00:12:50.538
So we all helped,
that's what I'm trying to

00:12:50.538 --> 00:12:50.894
say.

00:12:50.894 --> 00:12:54.462
We all helped with one great
aim in mind.

00:12:54.462 --> 00:12:55.621
It was clear.

00:12:55.621 --> 00:12:59.456
And you
know from what Professor Walker

00:12:59.456 --> 00:13:02.846
said, that the DNA structure,
in its

00:13:02.846 --> 00:13:08.147
structure held the clue to
crucial physiological behavior

00:13:08.147 --> 00:13:09.000
of DNA.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:13.636
And Crick and Watson said this
in their first paper,

00:13:13.636 --> 00:13:17.519
the structure
itself because of its

00:13:17.519 --> 00:13:23.612
complimentarity gives you an
immediate clue as to how it

00:13:23.612 --> 00:13:24.677
replicates.

00:13:24.677 --> 00:13:29.896
And replication of DNA
structure from generation to

00:13:29.896 --> 00:13:33.000
generation is,
of course, the

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.344
crucial thing about DNA.

00:13:35.344 --> 00:13:38.666
The copying,
the precise copying

00:13:38.666 --> 00:13:41.245
from generation to generation.

00:13:41.245 --> 00:13:44.818
And that fell out the of x-ray
structure.

00:13:44.818 --> 00:13:49.331
That's why the x-ray structure
was so very important,

00:13:49.331 --> 00:13:53.351
because it gave you an
immediate understanding of the

00:13:53.351 --> 00:13:56.771
role of DNA in
modern biology.

00:13:56.771 --> 00:14:00.000
So that's what we did.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:05.313
And eventually the people in
the group, the group got so

00:14:05.313 --> 00:14:09.650
overcrowded
they built a huge lab that was

00:14:09.650 --> 00:14:12.735
beautiful, like any new lab is.

00:14:12.735 --> 00:14:15.998
But
the thing I remember most of

00:14:15.998 --> 00:14:19.426
all was the atmosphere in that
place.

00:14:19.426 --> 00:14:22.345
So
remember, when you go and

00:14:22.345 --> 00:14:26.665
choose a lab,
choose one that's overcrowded.

00:14:26.665 --> 00:14:45.000
It will pay off. [APPLAUSE]

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:45.964
Thank you so much.

00:14:45.964 --> 00:14:47.357
That was really wonderful.

00:14:47.357 --> 00:14:48.000
Thank you.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:15:00.937
I don't know if some of you
realized

00:15:00.937 --> 00:15:04.215
quite how rare that was,
this discovery of the structure

00:15:04.215 --> 00:15:04.811
of DNA.

00:15:04.811 --> 00:15:07.921
As I said, probably one of the
big discoveries of mankind.

00:15:07.921 --> 00:15:09.358
Because, as
Vernon said,

00:15:09.358 --> 00:15:12.558
you could see so many of the
secrets of life as soon as

00:15:12.558 --> 00:15:13.850
you saw that structure.

00:15:13.850 --> 00:15:16.433
Very few people have ever heard
from someone

00:15:16.433 --> 00:15:17.894
who was there at the time.

00:15:17.894 --> 00:15:20.308
Maybe you'll forget a bunch of
stuff down

00:15:20.308 --> 00:15:23.520
the line, but I hope you'll
remember you heard somebody who

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:25.645
was there
when Watson and Crick were

00:15:25.645 --> 00:15:28.061
there and maybe his extra piece
of advice

00:15:28.061 --> 00:15:29.514
about choosing a lab.

00:15:29.514 --> 00:15:31.937
To say one thing quickly,
some of

00:15:31.937 --> 00:15:34.785
you I think understood what
I've been trying to do.

00:15:34.785 --> 00:15:37.175
I spent quite a
bit of time talking about

00:15:37.175 --> 00:15:39.684
science being done by real
people doing real

00:15:39.684 --> 00:15:40.434
experiments.

00:15:40.434 --> 00:15:41.996
Thanks for your comments.

00:15:41.996 --> 00:15:44.972
A few of you have gone
out of your way to say that

00:15:44.972 --> 00:15:47.433
this was a total waste of time
and you didn't

00:15:47.433 --> 00:15:50.654
understand why I didn't teach
you something instead of doing

00:15:50.654 --> 00:15:52.013
something
on the test.

00:15:52.013 --> 00:15:53.716
Well, I'm making up the test.

00:15:53.716 --> 00:15:56.661
And if you don't think
there'll be something on

00:15:56.661 --> 00:15:59.061
scientific process on the second
exam

00:15:59.061 --> 00:16:00.450
you'll be surprised.

00:16:00.450 --> 00:16:02.812
So I'm spending a lot of time
on

00:16:02.812 --> 00:16:05.429
this, and the reason is because
you are MIT students.

00:16:05.429 --> 00:16:07.937
You know, you can
go many places in the country

00:16:07.937 --> 00:16:10.059
to many high school biology
courses and

00:16:10.059 --> 00:16:12.095
you can memorize,
someone will tell you to

00:16:12.095 --> 00:16:15.412
memorize everything that's in
the book, and you'll get tested

00:16:15.412 --> 00:16:16.974
whether you can memorize it.

00:16:16.974 --> 00:16:18.649
You
guys are at MIT because you

00:16:18.649 --> 00:16:20.933
have the potential to be leaders
in whatever

00:16:20.933 --> 00:16:21.324
you do.

00:16:21.324 --> 00:16:24.559
I've made the transition from
being an undergrad sort of

00:16:24.559 --> 00:16:28.186
trying to memorize stuff in a
textbook to working

00:16:28.186 --> 00:16:29.563
on a cutting-edge.

00:16:29.563 --> 00:16:32.825
I've made some reasonably
significant discoveries in

00:16:32.825 --> 00:16:34.893
science, as have my other
colleagues in the

00:16:34.893 --> 00:16:37.099
department, some of them making
greater than I.

00:16:37.099 --> 00:16:39.687
But nevertheless if
you're on the cutting-edge then

00:16:39.687 --> 00:16:41.417
you're dealing with all the
stuff

00:16:41.417 --> 00:16:43.319
I'm trying to tell you about in
this thing.

00:16:43.319 --> 00:16:45.162
You're working as a part of
a group.

00:16:45.162 --> 00:16:46.371
There's competition.

00:16:46.371 --> 00:16:48.657
There are interpersonal
relationships.

