00:20:49.585 --> 00:20:56.005
10 to 20 billion
miles of DNA in each of our

00:20:56.005 --> 00:20:59.000
bodies, human DNA.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:03.125
They would go back and forth to
the sun multiple times.

00:21:03.125 --> 00:21:06.543
So that much
DNA had to get replicated in

00:21:06.543 --> 00:21:09.544
order for the fertilized egg we
all

00:21:09.544 --> 00:21:12.050
started out as to become you.

00:21:12.050 --> 00:21:14.816
Another thing,
the accuracy of

00:21:14.816 --> 00:21:18.149
replication is about ten to the
minus tenth.

00:21:18.149 --> 00:21:20.087
Most people,
including

00:21:20.087 --> 00:21:24.063
myself, don't have a very good
feel for exponents.

00:21:24.063 --> 00:21:27.288
So that's one
mistake in 10 billion.

00:21:27.288 --> 00:21:30.615
You know, it could be one
mistake in

00:21:30.615 --> 00:21:32.333
10 to the ninety-ninth.

00:21:32.333 --> 00:21:35.845
Well, what is one mistake in 10
billion mean?

00:21:35.845 --> 00:21:38.758
So let's relate it to something
we know.

00:21:38.758 --> 00:21:42.569
If I was typing let's say an
eight letter word,

00:21:42.569 --> 00:21:45.308
60 words a minute,
24 hours a day,

00:21:45.308 --> 00:21:48.647
7 days a
week, and I was as good as DNA

00:21:48.647 --> 00:21:51.536
replication, how often would I
make

00:21:51.536 --> 00:21:52.272
a mistake?

00:21:52.272 --> 00:21:56.031
So you can each think of how
long you think that is.

00:21:56.031 --> 00:21:58.511
But if
I was good on average,

00:21:58.511 --> 00:22:02.000
I would make a mistake once
every 38 years.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:06.907
So I'm about to tell you about
a process that's absolutely

00:22:06.907 --> 00:22:11.104
astonishing in terms of how
fast and how much you can do and

00:22:11.104 --> 00:22:13.919
with an
accuracy that goes beyond what

00:22:13.919 --> 00:22:16.303
we're used to in our ordinary
life.

00:22:16.303 --> 00:22:18.147
So
how does it do this?

00:22:18.147 --> 00:22:21.634
It has to be more than just
pulling the strands

00:22:21.634 --> 00:22:22.087
apart.

00:22:22.087 --> 00:22:26.544
And there's been some confusion
as to why I'm emphasizing

00:22:26.544 --> 00:22:28.314
5 prime and 3 prime.

00:22:28.314 --> 00:22:31.500
Well, each of these subunits,
each

00:22:31.500 --> 00:22:36.500
nucleotide, this is a 3 prime
hydroxyl and this is the 5 prime

00:22:36.500 --> 00:22:37.214
position.

00:22:37.214 --> 00:22:41.500
If we were joining together
subunits that had a hook

00:22:41.500 --> 00:22:45.953
and an eye it would make a
difference because it's not the

00:22:45.953 --> 00:22:47.455
same
on both ends.

00:22:47.455 --> 00:22:51.500
If we're going to start hooking
together it's exactly

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:55.156
the same thing when we get to a
biochemical level,

00:22:55.156 --> 00:22:58.807
the 5 prime end
is not the same as hydroxyl at

00:22:58.807 --> 00:23:01.500
the 3 prime end because the
whole

00:23:01.500 --> 00:23:04.215
thing is asymmetric.

00:23:04.215 --> 00:23:08.833
So the enzymes that copy DNA
are

00:23:08.833 --> 00:23:12.439
known as DNA polymerases.

00:23:12.439 --> 00:23:18.499
And it was a very difficult
challenge to

00:23:18.499 --> 00:23:26.123
figure out how they operated,
but Arthur Kornberg was the

00:23:26.123 --> 00:23:31.390
first person
to solve this problem.

00:23:31.390 --> 00:23:36.375
He was an extraordinarily
gifted

00:23:36.375 --> 00:23:37.420
biochemist.

00:23:37.420 --> 00:23:39.607
He's still at Stanford.

00:23:39.607 --> 00:23:43.125
And what he found was if we
have a

00:23:43.125 --> 00:23:47.560
5 prime end this would then be
the 3 prime end,

00:23:47.560 --> 00:23:52.575
and there's a 3 prime
hydroxyl which is this one

00:23:52.575 --> 00:23:53.717
right here.

00:23:53.717 --> 00:23:56.625
And this was paired,
say,

00:23:56.625 --> 00:23:59.533
with a C and A paired with a T.

00:23:59.533 --> 00:24:02.817
And let's say a G paired with a
C

00:24:02.817 --> 00:24:03.258
here.

00:24:03.258 --> 00:24:08.453
And let's say the next template
base was, let's make it a

00:24:08.453 --> 00:24:08.617
T.

00:24:08.617 --> 00:24:13.436
What Arthur Kornberg was able
to find was an enzyme activity

00:24:13.436 --> 00:24:16.907
that
catalyzed a template-dependent

00:24:16.907 --> 00:24:18.692
replication of DNA.

00:24:18.692 --> 00:24:21.761
That was
critical because he had to

00:24:21.761 --> 00:24:25.362
find, if you broke the cells
open, somewhere

00:24:25.362 --> 00:24:31.000
in that gamish of enzymes and
things from inside a cell.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:34.525
There had to be something that
was able to copy DNA.

00:24:34.525 --> 00:24:37.705
So in order to do
that he had to work out an

00:24:37.705 --> 00:24:38.120
assay.

00:24:38.120 --> 00:24:40.816
And he also had to have some
kind of

00:24:40.816 --> 00:24:45.284
guess as to what the cell would
be using in order to carry out

00:24:45.284 --> 00:24:46.435
the
synthesis.

00:24:46.435 --> 00:24:50.634
But one thing that was sort of
obvious was a DNA template

00:24:50.634 --> 00:24:52.738
because that was being copies.

00:24:52.738 --> 00:24:55.544
But the other part was you had
to have

00:24:55.544 --> 00:24:57.745
energy to form a covalent bond.

00:24:57.745 --> 00:25:00.443
So somehow there had to be
something

00:25:00.443 --> 00:25:04.354
that was sort of activated with
the energy built into the

00:25:04.354 --> 00:25:07.173
molecule so
that thermodynamically the

00:25:07.173 --> 00:25:10.220
whole thing would slide downhill
when you

00:25:10.220 --> 00:25:11.095
made a bond.

00:25:11.095 --> 00:25:14.233
And he knew that the cell had
triphosphates,

00:25:14.233 --> 00:25:17.729
just the
same type that we talked about

00:25:17.729 --> 00:25:20.000
when we talked about ATP.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:42.044
So this would be a 
deoxyribonucleotide

00:25:42.044 --> 00:25:43.541
triphosphate.

00:25:43.541 --> 00:25:47.570
And he was able to make a
guess,

00:25:47.570 --> 00:25:53.763
because he had to try things
until he found something that

00:25:53.763 --> 00:26:00.308
would work,
that this was what's used in

00:26:00.308 --> 00:26:03.000
DNA synthesis.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:08.616
So this hydroxyl ultimately
attacks this phosphate here.

00:26:08.616 --> 00:26:13.313
And these two
other phosphates then come off

00:26:13.313 --> 00:26:15.253
as a leaving group.

00:26:15.253 --> 00:26:20.575
So if we thought of
it as a P like this with two

00:26:20.575 --> 00:26:24.750
more Ps here,
these two come off and

00:26:24.750 --> 00:26:32.000
you get a new bond formed to
the phosphate.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:39.110
And so what Kornberg then was
able to find by using a DNA

00:26:39.110 --> 00:26:45.235
template that
had this sort of structure and

00:26:45.235 --> 00:26:50.284
P, P, P, like this,
that he was now

00:26:50.284 --> 00:26:54.938
able to get an A added here.

00:26:54.938 --> 00:27:01.891
This hydroxyl here became
the new hydroxyl.

00:27:01.891 --> 00:27:07.111
And so the direction of
synthesis,

00:27:07.111 --> 00:27:12.341
this strand is the other way,
so the direction of synthesis

00:27:12.341 --> 00:27:16.026
of a DNA
polymerase, it's polymerizing

00:27:16.026 --> 00:27:19.555
in the 5 prime to 3 prime
direction.

00:27:19.555 --> 00:27:24.199
This was again an amazing
discovery because it was the

00:27:24.199 --> 00:27:29.881
first time that
anyone had found an enzyme that

00:27:29.881 --> 00:27:32.000
could copy DNA.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.585
Arthur Kornberg got a Nobel
Prize for it.

00:27:34.585 --> 00:27:38.371
But at this point actually
genetics came in because there

00:27:38.371 --> 00:27:40.921
was a scientist John Cairns who
was at

00:27:40.921 --> 00:27:44.923
that point down at Cold Spring
Harbor, as I told you the other

00:27:44.923 --> 00:27:45.383
day.

00:27:45.383 --> 00:27:49.016
And John, in spite of the fact
that Arthur had found a DNA

00:27:49.016 --> 00:27:51.473
polymerase
that had all the properties

00:27:51.473 --> 00:27:54.307
that you would expect for
copying DNA, didn't

00:27:54.307 --> 00:27:57.687
think that was the one that
actually copied the DNA

00:27:57.687 --> 00:28:00.412
necessary for
cellular replication.

00:28:00.412 --> 00:28:03.307
So he reasoned if he was right
he'd

00:28:03.307 --> 00:28:07.452
be able to find a mutation that
would eliminate the activity of

00:28:07.452 --> 00:28:10.156
that
enzyme and the cell would still

00:28:10.156 --> 00:28:10.516
live.

00:28:10.516 --> 00:28:14.138
And so they did a screen,
and it was a lot of work,

00:28:14.138 --> 00:28:16.639
but they eventually found a
mutant of E.

00:28:16.639 --> 00:28:19.112
coli
that lacked this DNA polymerase

00:28:19.112 --> 00:28:21.325
that Arthur Kornberg had
discovered.

00:28:21.325 --> 00:28:23.726
And
the cell was still alive and

00:28:23.726 --> 00:28:25.824
was still replicating its DNA.

00:28:25.824 --> 00:28:28.307
So it
told both John and then Arthur

00:28:28.307 --> 00:28:31.000
there must be another enzyme in
the cell.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:32.188
And so Arthur went back.

00:28:32.188 --> 00:28:34.465
And now working in a mutant
that was missing

00:28:34.465 --> 00:28:37.452
this first polymerase he
discovered he found the one that

00:28:37.452 --> 00:28:38.886
really
replicates the DNA.

00:28:38.886 --> 00:28:40.443
The first one is important,
too.

00:28:40.443 --> 00:28:41.950
It's needed for
DNA repair.

00:28:41.950 --> 00:28:44.512
I'm going to talk to you about
that in next lecture,

00:28:44.512 --> 00:28:46.491
but
it's not absolutely crucial for

00:28:46.491 --> 00:28:46.754
life.

00:28:46.754 --> 00:28:49.857
And there's an interplay of
genetics and biochemistry.

00:28:49.857 --> 00:28:53.530
And you'll see I'm just sort of
foreshadowing what we're going

00:28:53.530 --> 00:28:56.543
to get to when we talk about
the genetics of this.

