You can see how the
crystallographers have fit the

00:30:09.844 --> 00:30:13.535
nucleotides right in the
crystal into these electron

00:30:13.535 --> 00:30:14.259
densities.

00:30:14.259 --> 00:30:16.876
And
here putting it together a bit

00:30:16.876 --> 00:30:19.690
in the blue is the secondary
structure

00:30:19.690 --> 00:30:22.699
of the protein and the
templates and whatnot.

00:30:22.699 --> 00:30:26.097
And I don't expect you to
see very much in that,

00:30:26.097 --> 00:30:29.538
but the point is I wanted to
sort of just set you

00:30:29.538 --> 00:30:32.055
up to show you this little
movie.

00:30:32.055 --> 00:30:35.902
Because DNA polymerases are
incredible machines.

00:30:35.902 --> 00:30:39.248
They copy at about a thousand
nucleotides a

00:30:39.248 --> 00:30:42.174
second and their accuracy is
really amazing.

00:30:42.174 --> 00:30:46.027
And I'll tell you all the
tricks to the accuracy in the

00:30:46.027 --> 00:30:48.913
next lecture,
but I want to show you this

00:30:48.913 --> 00:30:52.781
little movie because this is
sort of a simulation of what

00:30:52.781 --> 00:30:55.596
must happen
every time a nucleotide is

00:30:55.596 --> 00:30:56.022
added.

00:30:56.022 --> 00:30:58.582
Now, we'll see this over and
over

00:30:58.582 --> 00:31:00.732
again so I'll take it in
pieces.

00:31:00.732 --> 00:31:03.230
The yellow and the orange are
the

00:31:03.230 --> 00:31:04.716
secondary structures.

00:31:04.716 --> 00:31:06.274
That's an alpha helix.

00:31:06.274 --> 00:31:09.638
And certainly one
thing you can see is happening,

00:31:09.638 --> 00:31:12.152
as we're looking at this,
is the parts

00:31:12.152 --> 00:31:14.691
of the protein are moving
during this.

00:31:14.691 --> 00:31:18.489
So you can see this alpha
helix that's sort of swinging

00:31:18.489 --> 00:31:20.170
up and swinging back down.

00:31:20.170 --> 00:31:23.110
Now, what's
over here is the template base.

00:31:23.110 --> 00:31:25.538
That's the base that
correspondents

00:31:25.538 --> 00:31:30.000
to the T that I was just
showing you here.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.022
This is the incoming
nucleotide.

00:31:32.022 --> 00:31:34.306
There is the triphosphate
coming

00:31:34.306 --> 00:31:34.930
down here.

00:31:34.930 --> 00:31:37.115
And, in fact,
you just see those two

00:31:37.115 --> 00:31:38.176
phosphates going.

00:31:38.176 --> 00:31:39.912
So
what's happening here,

00:31:39.912 --> 00:31:42.922
this is going to be the end of
the growing chain.

00:31:42.922 --> 00:31:46.272
It's going attack right there,
join the phosphate and the

00:31:46.272 --> 00:31:47.916
pyrophosphate
will leave.

00:31:47.916 --> 00:31:51.538
And if you'll take a look,
when you see this movement of

00:31:51.538 --> 00:31:55.177
this helix from the beginning
state to up to here,

00:31:55.177 --> 00:31:57.284
you'll
see what happens.

00:31:57.284 --> 00:32:00.500
It's squeezing the template
base and

00:32:00.500 --> 00:32:02.852
the incoming nucleotide
together.

00:32:02.852 --> 00:32:05.500
What it's really doing is
testing

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:07.027
for the correct shape.

00:32:07.027 --> 00:32:10.500
Remember the shape of an A-T
base pair and a G-C

00:32:10.500 --> 00:32:12.166
base pair is the same.

00:32:12.166 --> 00:32:15.500
And if those of you who are
confused about

00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:19.013
guanine and the keto-enol
thing, try to draw hydrogen

00:32:19.013 --> 00:32:23.083
bonds with the enol
form of guanine and see how you

00:32:23.083 --> 00:32:23.333
do.

00:32:23.333 --> 00:32:27.261
I think you'll begin to
understand a bit.

00:32:27.261 --> 00:32:31.200
So at the heart of life is
something

00:32:31.200 --> 00:32:33.088
that can copy DNA.

00:32:33.088 --> 00:32:37.599
And there are these exquisitely
beautiful

00:32:37.599 --> 00:32:38.447
machines.

00:32:38.447 --> 00:32:44.000
The replicative machine in E.
coli has 18 proteins and the

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:49.101
ones in our bodies are even
more sophisticated with even

00:32:49.101 --> 00:32:50.400
more parts.

00:32:50.400 --> 00:32:50.720
OK.

00:32:50.720 --> 00:32:56.799
But to replicate a DNA molecule
there's another problem

00:32:56.799 --> 00:32:58.686
that comes up.

00:32:58.686 --> 00:33:17.662
Because DNA polymerases copy --
-- and grow chains in a 5 prime

00:33:17.662 --> 00:33:33.000
to 3
prime direction.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:37.312
And they need a 3 prime hydroxy
terminus.

00:33:37.312 --> 00:33:43.489
So they won't work if you
just gave it a single strand of

00:33:43.489 --> 00:33:43.896
DNA.

00:33:43.896 --> 00:33:47.664
No DNA polymerase can handle
that.

00:33:47.664 --> 00:33:53.830
It has to have something like
this where there's a template

00:33:53.830 --> 00:34:03.914
strand --
-- and there's what's known as

00:34:03.914 --> 00:34:06.433
the
primer strand.

00:34:06.433 --> 00:34:10.199
So there has to be something
that has the 3 prime

00:34:10.199 --> 00:34:14.237
hydroxyl and there has to be
something that's going to

00:34:14.237 --> 00:34:17.187
provide
the template that's going to be

00:34:17.187 --> 00:34:17.681
copied.

00:34:17.681 --> 00:34:21.677
So if we pull strands apart
like this with 5 prime to 3

00:34:21.677 --> 00:34:24.599
prime then they'll be 5 prime to
3 prime

00:34:24.599 --> 00:34:27.826
running in the opposite
direction.

00:34:27.826 --> 00:34:31.250
If we have a template like
this,

00:34:31.250 --> 00:34:38.641
this is OK because the strand
here can be copied 5 prime to 3

00:34:38.641 --> 00:34:39.750
prime.

00:34:39.750 --> 00:34:46.390
This is the new strand being
synthesized by the DNA

00:34:46.390 --> 00:34:48.250
polymerase.

00:34:48.250 --> 00:34:52.182
But what about the other
strand?

00:34:52.182 --> 00:34:56.750
The replication fork is moving
in

00:34:56.750 --> 00:35:01.921
this direction,
but if the -- So here is the 3

00:35:01.921 --> 00:35:04.548
to 5 prime
direction here.

00:35:04.548 --> 00:35:08.248
So if the DNA polymerase is
going to be copying

00:35:08.248 --> 00:35:11.769
this strand it's going to be
moving backwards to the

00:35:11.769 --> 00:35:14.385
direction of the
replication fork.

00:35:14.385 --> 00:35:17.914
Now, I guess evolution and
nature could have

00:35:17.914 --> 00:35:22.170
selected for two types of DNA
polymerases, one that copies 5

00:35:22.170 --> 00:35:25.248
prime
to 3 prime and one that copies

00:35:25.248 --> 00:35:27.581
in the opposite direction.

00:35:27.581 --> 00:35:29.142
But it didn't.

00:35:29.142 --> 00:35:33.863
And there are a number of
theoretical reasons that we

00:35:33.863 --> 00:35:36.460
could discuss in a more advanced
course

00:35:36.460 --> 00:35:38.195
perhaps for why that is true.

00:35:38.195 --> 00:35:40.768
But, in fact,
what it does is it uses the

00:35:40.768 --> 00:35:41.738
same polymerase.

00:35:41.738 --> 00:35:45.076
So as these things peel apart
the polymerase works in

00:35:45.076 --> 00:35:48.116
the other direction,
but there's another problem.

00:35:48.116 --> 00:35:51.082
If I just peel it
apart like this there's no 3

00:35:51.082 --> 00:35:51.993
prime hydroxyl.

00:35:51.993 --> 00:35:55.663
So it took people quite a
few years to figure out the

00:35:55.663 --> 00:35:58.000
strategy that's used in nature.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:04.361
Nature has a special enzyme
that makes a little piece of

00:36:04.361 --> 00:36:04.824
RNA.

00:36:04.824 --> 00:36:08.292
It's
called an RNA primer.

00:36:08.292 --> 00:36:13.500
And what it does is it provides
a 3 prime

00:36:13.500 --> 00:36:14.541
hydroxyl.

00:36:14.541 --> 00:36:21.250
And once you have the 3 prime
hydroxyl at the end of the

00:36:21.250 --> 00:36:29.000
little RNA chain then the DNA
polymerase --

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:39.856
-- can be made 5 prime to 3
prime.

00:36:39.856 --> 00:36:45.398
So as you peel open the
replication fork then little

00:36:45.398 --> 00:36:50.945
pieces of RNA are
used to make a new strand of

00:36:50.945 --> 00:36:53.959
DNA and it goes this way.

00:36:53.959 --> 00:36:59.520
Now that
obviously doesn't give you a

00:36:59.520 --> 00:37:03.000
new intact DNA strand.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:08.123
And part of the clue to this
working out what was going on at

00:37:08.123 --> 00:37:11.096
DNA
replication was the recognition

00:37:11.096 --> 00:37:14.271
that newly synthesized DNA was
made as

00:37:14.271 --> 00:37:15.432
little pieces.

00:37:15.432 --> 00:37:19.327
And then later it got joined
into longer pieces.

00:37:19.327 --> 00:37:22.323
And
the person who discovered this

00:37:22.323 --> 00:37:23.289
was Okazaki.

00:37:23.289 --> 00:37:27.925
So these fragments of DNA
that are synthesized initially

00:37:27.925 --> 00:37:31.181
are called Okazaki fragments,
after the

00:37:31.181 --> 00:37:33.290
person who discovered this.

00:37:33.290 --> 00:37:36.181
It was rather puzzling because
when

00:37:36.181 --> 00:37:39.761
you tried to look at the
synthesis of DNA you're looking

00:37:39.761 --> 00:37:42.475
at a long
molecule, and you found some of

00:37:42.475 --> 00:37:44.907
the newly synthesized material
was in

00:37:44.907 --> 00:37:45.779
short pieces.

00:37:45.779 --> 00:37:48.599
And as you watched over time it
got longer.

00:37:48.599 --> 00:37:51.132
So the
cell, I think you can sort of

00:37:51.132 --> 00:37:53.635
see from first principles what
has to

00:37:53.635 --> 00:37:57.756
happen here then.

00:37:57.756 --> 00:38:06.000
That in order to come and make
--

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:09.000
This strand is pretty easy to
do,

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:14.000
but what the cells have to do
now is they've got these little

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:22.000
RNA primers.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:27.884
And then they remove the RNA by
an enzyme that's capable of

00:38:27.884 --> 00:38:34.205
degrading
the DNA or clipping it at the

00:38:34.205 --> 00:38:36.000
junction.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:40.900
And that then leaves the cell
in this sort of situation where

00:38:40.900 --> 00:38:44.086
there
are little tiny gaps in between

00:38:44.086 --> 00:38:45.720
these pieces of DNA.

00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:49.283
But at the end
of each one of these is a 3

00:38:49.283 --> 00:38:50.490
prime hydroxyl.

00:38:50.490 --> 00:38:55.257
So another polymerase or
one or another polymerase in

00:38:55.257 --> 00:39:00.325
the cell can fill those little
pieces of DNA out.

00:39:00.325 --> 00:39:04.300
And then there's one little
nick

00:39:04.300 --> 00:39:06.629
that needs to be sealed.

00:39:06.629 --> 00:39:10.900
And so what you finally end up
with is a 3

00:39:10.900 --> 00:39:15.800
prime hydroxyl here,
a 5 prime phosphate that's at

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:19.791
the other end,
and then these are joined

00:39:19.791 --> 00:39:20.616
together.

00:39:20.616 --> 00:39:24.099
This is one nucleotide here and
the

00:39:24.099 --> 00:39:25.234
other here.

00:39:25.234 --> 00:39:30.699
These are then joined together
to give the ordinary

00:39:30.699 --> 00:39:39.000
phosphodiester bond that links
--

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:42.089
-- the two nucleotides together
like that.

00:39:42.089 --> 00:39:47.007
And the enzyme that does that
is an enzyme called DNA ligase.

00:39:47.007 --> 00:39:50.000
You can almost think about it
as DNA

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:54.039
Scotch tape that will take a
little nick in DNA,

00:39:54.039 --> 00:39:57.800
if we've got a
phosphate and hydroxyl,

00:39:57.800 --> 00:40:01.000
and it will join them together.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:06.062
So this process of replication,
which can go at about a

00:40:06.062 --> 00:40:09.686
thousand
nucleotides a second with this

00:40:09.686 --> 00:40:13.000
amazing degree of accuracy,
uses two

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:17.956
different DNA polymerases,
both of which biochemically can

00:40:17.956 --> 00:40:20.183
only go in
one direction.

00:40:20.183 --> 00:40:25.000
But you can see they have to be
somehow oriented so that

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:30.239
one of them is able to move in
this direction and the other one

00:40:30.239 --> 00:40:33.245
is able
to move in that direction.

00:40:33.245 --> 00:40:36.181
The key part in this sort of
the

00:40:36.181 --> 00:40:39.755
course is to try and understand
this 5 to 3 prime and to get

00:40:39.755 --> 00:40:42.434
this basic
idea that nature had to do

00:40:42.434 --> 00:40:43.161
something.

00:40:43.161 --> 00:40:46.877
It was fairly easy to
copy one strand because that

00:40:46.877 --> 00:40:50.930
was sort of the direction of the
polymerase movement was the

00:40:50.930 --> 00:40:53.635
same as the replication fork
movement, but

00:40:53.635 --> 00:40:58.000
the other strand had to have
been much more a problem.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:00.848
And so when you get down to a
biochemical level,

00:41:00.848 --> 00:41:03.369
though, it's very
conceptually easy to say,

00:41:03.369 --> 00:41:06.000
oh, you've got complimentary
strands so we just

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.885
take it apart,
we take the photograph and the

00:41:08.885 --> 00:41:11.681
negative and we
make the opposite one and now

00:41:11.681 --> 00:41:12.898
we've got two copies.

00:41:12.898 --> 00:41:15.552
When you get down
to the biochemical details

00:41:15.552 --> 00:41:18.000
there is this major biochemical
issue of

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:21.314
whether the polymerase can go
in the 3 prime or the 5 prime

00:41:21.314 --> 00:41:22.000
direction.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:25.529
And nature has chosen to do it
all or has been selected to do

00:41:25.529 --> 00:41:28.530
it all
somehow with a polymerase going

00:41:28.530 --> 00:41:30.000
in one direction.

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:33.707
There are many other aspects to
DNA replication.

00:41:33.707 --> 00:41:37.978
And one of the tricks
that I find most fascinating is

00:41:37.978 --> 00:41:41.199
that these polymerases,
once they get on

00:41:41.199 --> 00:41:42.540
DNA they stay on.

00:41:42.540 --> 00:41:46.800
And that's part of the secret
because it takes about

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:51.039
a millisecond to add a
nucleotide, but if it comes off

00:41:51.039 --> 00:41:54.266
the DNA it has
to get back on.

00:41:54.266 --> 00:41:58.000
Then it takes about a minute.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:01.873
So the whole trick to being a
very, very fast DNA polymerase

00:42:01.873 --> 00:42:04.056
is to
somehow hang onto the DNA.

00:42:04.056 --> 00:42:06.798
So what biochemists did was
they purified

00:42:06.798 --> 00:42:10.242
the actual enzymatic activity
that could carry out this

00:42:10.242 --> 00:42:12.971
process, and
then they started to look for

00:42:12.971 --> 00:42:15.599
other protein factors that would
help the

00:42:15.599 --> 00:42:17.205
process to work better.

00:42:17.205 --> 00:42:19.998
And they discovered something
called a

00:42:19.998 --> 00:42:24.004
processivity factor which made
the polymerase stay on the DNA.

00:42:24.004 --> 00:42:26.210
And
people wondered for a lot of

00:42:26.210 --> 00:42:28.798
years how that worked and why
did this

00:42:28.798 --> 00:42:30.406
system work so well.

00:42:30.406 --> 00:42:33.460
And finally the crystal
structure of

00:42:33.460 --> 00:42:36.578
the processivity factor was
discovered.

00:42:36.578 --> 00:42:40.502
And if I go back to
this sort of diagram where this

00:42:40.502 --> 00:42:43.304
is the piece of DNA that's
copied, what

00:42:43.304 --> 00:42:47.910
it turned out was that the
processivity factor is basically

00:42:47.910 --> 00:42:50.083
a
doughnut that kind of gets

00:42:50.083 --> 00:42:52.367
clamped around the DNA like
that.

00:42:52.367 --> 00:42:55.150
So it's
sort of like taking a washer

00:42:55.150 --> 00:42:58.076
with a place where you can pry
it apart

00:42:58.076 --> 00:43:02.324
opening it up,
putting it around the DNA like

00:43:02.324 --> 00:43:03.000
this.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:06.660
And then the polymerase,
more or less since this is

00:43:06.660 --> 00:43:09.190
topologically
linked to the DNA,

00:43:09.190 --> 00:43:11.757
is like a washer sliding on a
wire.

00:43:11.757 --> 00:43:14.929
This DNA
polymerase hangs onto that and

00:43:14.929 --> 00:43:16.440
it doesn't come off.

00:43:16.440 --> 00:43:19.734
And I think
there's a little picture of it.

00:43:19.734 --> 00:43:21.321
Here's a little movie.

00:43:21.321 --> 00:43:24.333
There's the
DNA going through and this is

00:43:24.333 --> 00:43:25.714
one of these clamps.

00:43:25.714 --> 00:43:30.148
It's virtually the
same structure in a bacterium

00:43:30.148 --> 00:43:32.000
and inside of us.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:35.419
But, in fact,
the amino acids are almost all

00:43:35.419 --> 00:43:36.215
different.

00:43:36.215 --> 00:43:39.025
But the
underlying structure of the

00:43:39.025 --> 00:43:41.032
protein is almost identical.

00:43:41.032 --> 00:43:44.450
And there are
special machines called clamp

00:43:44.450 --> 00:43:47.269
loaders that pry open this
clamps,

00:43:47.269 --> 00:43:51.203
clamp them around DNA,
and that's part of the secret

00:43:51.203 --> 00:43:54.108
to how these
polymerases are able to

00:43:54.108 --> 00:43:55.856
polymerize DNA so fast.

00:43:55.856 --> 00:43:59.639
There are a lot of
other pieces of this machinery.

00:43:59.639 --> 00:44:02.250
If you go on you'll hear more
about

00:44:02.250 --> 00:44:02.571
them.

00:44:02.571 --> 00:44:06.107
I just want to give you one of
the most recent insights.

00:44:06.107 --> 00:44:08.312
I mean
this, as you might guess,

00:44:08.312 --> 00:44:11.250
since DNA replication is at the
heart of life

00:44:11.250 --> 00:44:14.473
it's been studied very,
very hard, ever since the

00:44:14.473 --> 00:44:16.119
discovery of DNA
helix.

00:44:16.119 --> 00:44:17.784
My colleague,
Alan Grossman,

00:44:17.784 --> 00:44:20.250
made quite a discovery just
probably

00:44:20.250 --> 00:44:21.815
three or four years ago.

00:44:21.815 --> 00:44:24.750
He took that green fluorescent
protein that

00:44:24.750 --> 00:44:28.488
we've seen a few times,
and he actually joined the gene

00:44:28.488 --> 00:44:31.540
encoding
green fluorescent protein to

00:44:31.540 --> 00:44:35.139
the backend of a piece of
the DNA polymerase.

00:44:35.139 --> 00:44:37.846
So wherever the DNA polymerase
went

00:44:37.846 --> 00:44:40.251
now there was a little
fluorescent molecule.

00:44:40.251 --> 00:44:42.958
And he looked to see
where it was in the cell.

00:44:42.958 --> 00:44:45.230
And I, like many other people,
had for

00:44:45.230 --> 00:44:46.781
years taught,
and this is why,

00:44:46.781 --> 00:44:48.922
you know, I have respect for
the fact

00:44:48.922 --> 00:44:51.585
that I'm just teaching you the
current model.

00:44:51.585 --> 00:44:53.457
For much of my
career I taught,

00:44:53.457 --> 00:44:56.306
so DNA polymerase is sort of
like a train going down

00:44:56.306 --> 00:45:00.000
the tracks a thousand molecules
per second.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:05.808
And we're doing all this stuff
with the leading and with the

00:45:05.808 --> 00:45:07.151
two
strands.

00:45:07.151 --> 00:45:12.046
So let me just put those words
up while I'm up there.

00:45:12.046 --> 00:45:14.156
This
one is called,

00:45:14.156 --> 00:45:19.199
this strand that's easy to
replicate is called the

00:45:19.199 --> 00:45:20.675
leading strand.

00:45:20.675 --> 00:45:25.599
And this one where you have to
do the primer and

00:45:25.599 --> 00:45:32.000
whatnot is called the lagging
strand.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.268
In any case,
what I had taught was that

00:45:34.268 --> 00:45:37.161
polymerase was like a train
running on tracks.

00:45:37.161 --> 00:45:40.000
You could calculate how fast it
would move.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:44.000
What Alan, to his amazement,
found was when he looked to see

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:47.411
where the DNA polymerase was,
it wasn't spread out all over

00:45:47.411 --> 00:45:49.552
the cell
as if you thought it was a

00:45:49.552 --> 00:45:50.985
thing running on tracks.

00:45:50.985 --> 00:45:53.464
In fact, it was
in the center of the cell.

00:45:53.464 --> 00:45:56.000
And then late in cell division
it split into

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:00.000
two spots that went to the
midpoints of what would be the

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:01.440
daughter cells.

00:46:01.440 --> 00:46:04.800
And so what he ended up
realizing

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:09.721
from that was that instead it
was more as if the polymerase

00:46:09.721 --> 00:46:12.898
was a
factory and it pulled the DNA

00:46:12.898 --> 00:46:16.000
through it rather than it
traveling

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:18.191
down the tracks of the DNA.

00:46:18.191 --> 00:46:21.599
And that was a very surprising
discovery

00:46:21.599 --> 00:46:26.239
that went against all the dogma
and all the pictures in the

00:46:26.239 --> 00:46:27.199
textbook.

00:46:27.199 --> 00:46:29.530
And it was a discovery at MIT.

00:46:29.530 --> 00:46:32.250
That was published in,
I think it

00:46:32.250 --> 00:46:35.823
was 2001, something like that,
a very recent discovery.

00:46:35.823 --> 00:46:37.354
Things keep
changing.

00:46:37.354 --> 00:46:41.250
That's again why I keep
emphasizing I cannot teach you a

00:46:41.250 --> 00:46:42.293
fact in biology.

00:46:42.293 --> 00:46:45.750
I can teach you the best
understanding we have that

00:46:45.750 --> 00:46:47.867
explains the experiments to
date.

00:46:47.867 --> 00:46:50.250
But somebody may make a
discovery

00:46:50.250 --> 00:46:50.861
tomorrow.

00:46:50.861 --> 00:46:54.192
That means we'll have to change
our understanding.

00:46:54.192 --> 00:46:54.396
OK?

00:46:54.396 --> 00:46:56.095
So good luck on the exam.

00:46:56.095 --> 00:46:57.961
Ill see you on Monday,
OK?

